  "prompt_text": "A chess board has 64 squares. Two opposite corners are removed. Can you cover the remaining 62 squares with dominoes that each cover exactly 2 adjacent squares? Prove your answer.",
  "response_text": "To determine if it is possible to cover the remaining 62 squares of a chessboard with dominoes after removing two opposite corners, we need to analyze the problem step-by-step.\n\n### Step-by-Step Analysis\n\n1. **Initial Setup**: A standard chessboard has 64 squares, alternating between black and white. Each domino covers exactly one black and one white square. Therefore, for a complete tiling with dominoes, the number of black and white squares must be equal, which is true for a full 8x8 chessboard (32 black and 32 white).\n\n2. **Removing Corners**: When we remove two opposite corners, we are removing two squares of the same color. This means we are left with 32 squares of one color and 30 squares of the other color. For example, if we remove the top-left and bottom-right corners, we remove two black squares, leaving us with 30 black and 32 white squares.\n\n3. **Domino Tiling Requirement**: Since each domino must cover one black and one white square, in order to completely tile the board with dominoes, the number of black and white squares must be equal. However, after removing the two opposite corners, we have an imbalance of 2 squares (32 - 30 = 2), meaning there will always be 2 more squares of one color than the other.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nGiven that the remaining board has an unequal number of black and white squares (30 black and 32 white or vice versa), it is impossible to cover the entire board with dominoes, as each domino requires one black and one white square.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 7\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
